name: Value Scientist
tweet: @Chariot_Invest 30 years is a looong time. The longer your horizon, the more uncertainty. I haven't followed $TDG, but it generally goes: if you're making high ROIC, it attracts competition. tweet: @___mike_____ Agree fully. I stay away from ridiculous TAM expansion high growth companies precisely because i am uncomfortable with what is being discounted at those prices. But in this market any whiff of "quality" is being swept up. $TDG P/fwd sales is up 3 turns in just 5 months

name: Irving Soh
tweet: @Chariot_Invest @HorizonKinetics That depends. 30 year time-frames require explicit insight into reinvestment moats. Does $tdg HV a moat it can keep pouring money into at high rates of return ala $cmg or $dpz? Idk the answer. But u prob do. That's part one. Part two is the relative intrisnci value compound calc.

name: Mike
tweet: @Chariot_Invest So, afterall, with names like $TDG, there is a great luxury to be had, because the price follows the underlying value pretty closely most of the time, while, of course, the discount the 'intrinsic value' might remain deep for multiple years.

name: Mike
tweet: @Chariot_Invest 0.02 from me on managing a position in a stock like $TDG. There are stocks like $TDG or $V or $TMO that just experience uninterrupted compunding at a 20%+ ROIC many years, often boosted with smartly conducted buyback policy.

name: Charioteer Investing
tweet: @chasingthevig @HorizonKinetics Agree, and that is the hardest part. I've studied $TDG so much that i'm convinced i'm correct. Maybe not for 30 yrs but at least for 15 yrs (assuming an earlier than avg aircraft retirement age). It's uneconomical to buy those parts from anyone besides $TDG, the moat seems huge..

name: Abhinav Shah
tweet: @Chariot_Invest How confident are you that $TDG can take price increases for 30 years with no competition? I presume very from your thread, but seems like a bold assumption?

name: Charioteer Investing
tweet: Any thoughts from the Twitter-verse? Not necessarily about $TDG specifically...but this line of thinking in general? In a way it reminds me of Stahl at @HorizonKinetics continually buying $TPL at seemingly any valuation. His results speak for themselves.

name: Charioteer Investing
tweet: But if i view it from the lens of 30 years of LSD/MSD growth virtually unreliant on volume because they can raise prices consistently...is it really that expensive? Why shouldn't i just keep adding to my $TDG position every month, near term valuation be damned?

name: Charioteer Investing
tweet: I doubled my $TDG position in April 2020, and now it has run up so much that it seems optically expensive (esp in the context of the worst Aero downturn of all time). I haven't added any new capital to that position as it has run up...

name: Charioteer Investing
tweet: It makes me feel like rather than look for new stocks, I should concentrate on my largest positions like $TDG and $ROP, and just keep adding. Once $TDG gets a part on a plane, it has a 30 year runway to raise price MSD annually with zero competition.
